JOHANNESBURG – South Africa’s Kevin Anderson dropped one spot to 16th in the latest ATP rankings released on Monday. Anderson had an incredible run in the US Open where made it to the final before losing to Spain’s Rafael Nadal on September 11. Anderson, at the time, was the world No 32, was the lowest-ranked US Open men’s singles finalist since the inception of the ATP rankings in 1973. The South African started the season at No 80 in the ATP Rankings after an injury-ravaged 2016. It was his lowest mark since August 2010. Anderson reached a career-high ranking of 10th in October 2015 soon after beating Murray to reach the US Open quarterfinals. Full SA rankings:
